   <titles>
      <title>The Norm of a Vector</title>
      <plain.title>Norm</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The length of a vector is just the length of any arrow <subordinate>
                     <hot>representing</hot>
                     <info>
                        <info.caption>arrow representing a vector</info.caption>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Recall that a vector consists of all those arrows of a given direction and length. Any one of these arrows is said to represent the vector.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate> it. In this section we present the basic properties of the norm operation on vectors.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_NormOfVector">
               <caption>Norm of a Vector</caption>
               <associate type="Example">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Example of a Norm Computation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The norm of the vector <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x} = (1,2,2)</latex>
                           </math> in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                           </math> is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>\abs{\Vect{x}} = \sqrt{ 1^2 + 2^2 + 2^2 } = 3</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <associate type="Comment">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Comment</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Thus the length of <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> is obtained by summing up the squares of the components of <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, and then taking the square root.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The length or norm of a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> is given by </para.body>
                     <index.symbol>
                        <symbol>
                           <math>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}|</latex>
                           </math>
                        </symbol>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>|\Vect{x}|</latex>
                                 </math> denotes the norm or length of a vector.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.symbol>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>length</term>
                        <term>of a vector</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The length of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                                 </math> in <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                 </math> is given by</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| := \sqrt{x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                           </math.display>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click to jump to the section where it is defined.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>vector</term>
                        <term>length</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The length of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                                 </math> in <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                 </math> is given by</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| := \sqrt{x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                           </math.display>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click to jump to the section where it is defined.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>norm</term>
                        <term>of a vector</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The norm or length of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                                 </math> in <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                 </math> is given by</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| := \sqrt{x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                           </math.display>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click to jump to the section where it is defined.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>vector</term>
                        <term>norm</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The norm of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                                 </math> in <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                 </math> its length. It is given by</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| := \sqrt{x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                           </math.display>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click to jump to the section where it is defined.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>|\Vect{x}| := \sqrt{x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>By design, <math>
                     <latex>|\Vect{x}|</latex>
                  </math> is a non-negative number which gives the 
